WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.032 --> 00:00:08.240
MALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:12.300
Welcome to Talks at Google
in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:16.680
Today it's my great pleasure
to introduce Robert Shiller.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:20.730
Dr. Shiller is Sterling
Professor of Economics at Yale

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:25.870
and winner of the 2013
Nobel Prize in economics.

00:00:25.870 --> 00:00:29.280
He's the author of the New York
Times best seller "Irrational

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:34.200
Exuberance," and with George
Akerlof, also a Nobel winner,

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:38.760
he's coauthored a previous
book in addition to today's.

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:41.790
Dr. Shiller joins
us today to discuss

00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:45.490
the provocatively titled
"Phishing for Fools:

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:49.470
The Economics of
Manipulation and Deception."

00:00:49.470 --> 00:00:52.090
As he says in the
book, "Competitive

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:56.540
markets by their very nature
spawn deception and trickery

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:59.420
as a result of the same
profit motives that

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:01.565
give us our prosperity."

00:01:01.565 --> 00:01:04.090
I'll let him take it from there.

00:01:04.090 --> 00:01:06.839
Please join me in
welcoming Bob Shiller.

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:10.751
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:17.780
ROBERT SHILLER: Thank you.

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:20.190
Jonathan told me
that you recently had

00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:25.000
Dick Thaler in the same series.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.030
That's interesting to me.

00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:29.450
Dick is an old
colleague of mine.

00:01:29.450 --> 00:01:32.450
We've been running a
behavioral economics workshop

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:39.170
at the NBER, which is right
near here, for 25 years.

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:44.530
And he wrote a book called
"Nudge" with Cass Sunstein

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:47.470
about government policy.

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:48.970
And the book I'm
going to talk about

00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:51.560
could be considered
the anti "Nudge."

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:53.990
It's kind of the opposite.

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:58.090
The presumption was that nudges
are used for good purposes,

00:01:58.090 --> 00:01:59.160
and maybe they are.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:01.160
Do you know what a nudge is?

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:05.070
This is a new-- I'm drifting
from my prepared talk.

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:11.370
We're all critical
of economists.

00:02:11.370 --> 00:02:15.910
There aren't any economist
here, probably, right?

00:02:15.910 --> 00:02:20.970
So economists have
adopted a canonical model

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:25.650
of an economy consisting of self
interested, utility maximizing

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:28.780
individuals who take
prices as a given

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:34.020
and maximize their
utility individually.

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:36.030
And that leaves to
some kind of optimality

00:02:36.030 --> 00:02:42.640
ultimately in the
equilibrium that follows.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:49.230
So both Thaler and I are
critical of that model

00:02:49.230 --> 00:02:51.090
that underlies economics.

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:53.630
And our criticism
has something to do

00:02:53.630 --> 00:03:01.610
with the field of psychology,
of neuroscience, sociology,

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:05.086
which have a different approach
to studying human nature.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:11.760
I feel a little uncomfortable
talking at Google.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:16.700
I don't think I prepared
adequately for you.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:21.014
That's because a lot of what
we talk about is marketing,

00:03:21.014 --> 00:03:23.980
and we have an
uncomfortable relationship

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:25.940
to marketing as you'll see.

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:30.320
Not necessarily negative,
but just uncomfortable.

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:32.910
And I don't know what
Google, isn't Google,

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:34.680
there's different
ways of looking at it.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:38.286
By the way, you're Google
not Alphabet, right?

00:03:38.286 --> 00:03:40.465
AUDIENCE: There's
some Alphabet here.

