00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:59.020
Now that is definitely
not a news story

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:03.560
for me in the sense that
it's wasting my time.

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:07.560
So I've had this good
feeling about Google, largely

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:11.080
from that, well, in many things.

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:21.695
So what this book is about
is about what's really,

00:06:21.695 --> 00:06:27.750
it's a certain kind of general
problem with free market,

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:30.610
unregulated economies.

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:34.600
And by the way, the
co-author, George Akerlof

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:39.950
is as you mentioned is my
coauthor on another book,

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:45.250
he to me is a very
independent thinking person.

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:47.670
I wanted to write a book with
him not quite knowing where

00:06:47.670 --> 00:06:53.210
it would go, because I
like working with people

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:54.930
who think differently.

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:57.110
And both he and I
have always felt

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:00.510
somewhat critical about what
goes on in our profession.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:07.090
The point is to bring that out.

00:07:07.090 --> 00:07:09.510
Now, the problem--
or also, what is

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:12.460
a fool, that's our coined word.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:15.380
That's someone who may
be very intelligent,

00:07:15.380 --> 00:07:19.660
but doesn't appreciate how much
manipulation and deception is

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:22.690
being foisted on him.

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:25.700
So the idea of our
book is that we

00:07:25.700 --> 00:07:29.160
would talk about many
different kinds of manipulation

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:29.980
and deception.

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:32.030
Talk about it from
a behavioral, from

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:34.900
a psychological standpoint.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:38.570
And another thing about our book
is that we're different from,

00:07:38.570 --> 00:07:43.970
there's a long history of books
on this topic as you may know.

00:07:43.970 --> 00:07:48.090
We wanted to take it from a
more economic perspective.

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:51.630
With both George Akerlof and
I, when we were teenagers,

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:55.975
we didn't know each other then,
we read Vance Packard's book

00:07:55.975 --> 00:07:56.975
"The Hidden Persuaders."

00:07:56.975 --> 00:07:57.990
Do you know this book?

00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:02.250
It was a bestseller
in the 1950s.

00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:09.510
It detailed how advertisers
use psychology to trick you.

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:13.320
And you are already aware that
they do that sometimes, but you

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:16.280
read Vance Packard's book,
and it comes across looking

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:19.600
much more frequent.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:21.390
The problem with
Vance Packard's book,

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:24.030
though, is that it doesn't
have any economics in it,

00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:27.340
and it seems to
portray the marketers

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:30.370
as an evil conspiracy.

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:33.770
And we didn't feel that that
was the right way to look at it.

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:41.960
So our book is about what we
call a "phishing equilibrium."

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:44.800
It's not that people
are evil, it's

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:52.538
that we have a market
system that allows,

00:08:52.538 --> 00:08:56.160
that almost forces
people to play the tricks

00:08:56.160 --> 00:09:05.830
that we don't like, and it's
called competitive pressures.

00:09:05.830 --> 00:09:09.090
So the theory of
competitive equilibrium

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:13.080
is sometimes connected to
Darwin's theory of evolution,

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:17.220
constant pressure on
businesses to make profits,

00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:20.300
and that means
then that they will

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:23.080
be very efficient, because
they will be struggling hard

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:24.270
to succeed.

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:26.540
But the problem
is that they might

00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:31.020
have to be dishonest
within subtle,

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:33.030
it has to be within
the law, of course.

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:37.920
But this more subtle
form of dishonesty

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:41.809
underlies problems that
we see in free markets.

00:09:41.809 --> 00:09:43.350
We're going to come
around at the end

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:47.620
to a plea for civil
society, or an argument

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.300
that civil society
is what really

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:55.620
matters in a successful
free market economy.

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:58.270
By the way, I should
add since I'm here,

00:09:58.270 --> 00:10:00.310
I believe in free
markets, and in fact, I

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:04.390
have something of an
entrepreneurial history.

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:07.650
I started with Case
and Weiss, a company

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:10.760
called Case, Shiller,
Weiss in 1991

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:15.770
that produced home price
indices and valuations.

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:17.630
We were ahead of Zillow.

00:10:17.630 --> 00:10:24.720
We had an online in the mid
1990s home valuation service.

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:27.640
And the outcome wasn't
as successful as Zillow,

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:31.690
but we sold our company in 2002.

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:37.910
And now Core Logic is
continuing our index production.

00:10:37.910 --> 00:10:41.380
And we've established a futures
market for single family homes

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.240
based on our indexes,
and that's still

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:46.790
going, not hugely successful,
but Standard and Poor's

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:48.670
publishes our indexes.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:50.610
So that was our
successful venture.

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:54.560
Then we had an unsuccessful one
that I won't tell you about.

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:57.740
But it may not be
unsuccessful, because I

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:59.950
think that what we
tried, which was

00:10:59.950 --> 00:11:02.200
to create markets
for real estate

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:09.260
and oil and other maybe GDP
is still being talked about.

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:13.080
I think the story
is not over yet.

00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:19.720
So I'm really pro free markets
and pro entrepreneurship.

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.070
This is just a, what
I'm talking about,

00:11:22.070 --> 00:11:26.110
what we're talking about in this
book is just a dent into that.

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:28.750
And it's don't go too
far with the belief

00:11:28.750 --> 00:11:36.040
in that just self interest will
promote good economic outcomes.

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:43.210
So I think that one thing that
economists don't recognize

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:46.540
is how the world is
driven by social movements

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:48.750
and thought leaders.

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:57.870
And they tend to,
one of the problems

00:11:57.870 --> 00:12:02.570
is that, there's many
problems that are,

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:06.130
but in terms of our
thinking as academics,

00:12:06.130 --> 00:12:12.440
there's a tendency to be
affected by prevailing theory.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:17.510
Something that Daniel Kahneman
calls theory induced blindness.

00:12:17.510 --> 00:12:20.490
A theory becomes established
as part of a movement,

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:23.610
and then it gets tremendous
prestige for a while,

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.405
and then it becomes overrated.

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:33.200
And I think what
George and I want

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:38.130
to argue against in our
book is the overratedness

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:41.910
of the free market
capitalism idea.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:49.000
So let me step back
and think about, I

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.910
don't know if any of you had
graduate training in economics.

00:12:52.910 --> 00:12:55.403
Probably some of you have
had undergraduate training.

00:12:58.510 --> 00:13:02.540
There is one of
the core elements

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:05.440
that you will be taught
in a economic theory

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:09.450
course will be something
called the fundamental theorem

00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:12.140
of welfare economics.

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:14.202
Do you know this?

00:13:14.202 --> 00:13:15.380
At least one of you doesn't.

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:22.470
Whether you've heard of the
exact theorem is irrelevant.

00:13:22.470 --> 00:13:25.770
I think you've heard of the
general sense of conclusion

00:13:25.770 --> 00:13:27.070
from it.

00:13:27.070 --> 00:13:30.380
The fundamental theorem
of welfare economics,

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:34.770
which you can find in
micro theory textbooks,

00:13:34.770 --> 00:13:37.560
is a mathematical
theorem that describes

00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:39.980
a competitive equilibrium.

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:44.950
You assume that each individual
is completely selfish, only

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:47.960
interested in
himself or herself,

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:52.140
and this person
maximizes utilities

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:54.810
subject to a budget constraint.

00:13:54.810 --> 00:13:58.480
They're also producers that
produce the commodities,

00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:01.680
and they maximize their profits
subject to a budget constraint.

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:05.080
But there is no social
feeling whatsoever.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:10.080
Everyone does it for
personal reward only.

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:14.290
The outcome, the theorem says,
is in a competitive equilibrium

00:14:14.290 --> 00:14:19.650
if there are no externalities,
that the allocation of goods

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:22.700
and services will
be Pareto optimal.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:24.420
You ever heard of this term?

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:25.950
Some of you have.

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:29.740
Vilfredo Pareto was
an economic theorist

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:32.240
who flourished around 1900.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:35.500
And he actually anticipated
the fundamental theorem

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:40.240
of welfare economics, but
didn't prove it adequately.

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:45.950
The Pareto optimality
means there is no way

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:48.410
to make everyone better off.

00:14:48.410 --> 00:14:52.030
You can redistribute income, you
can take from one to another,

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:54.840
and that will make one better
off and the other worse off,

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.740
but there is no
way in equilibrium

00:14:56.740 --> 00:14:59.270
to make everyone better off.

00:14:59.270 --> 00:15:03.330
Moreover, this became accepted
by economics departments

00:15:03.330 --> 00:15:06.730
who then thought, well,
redistribution is not

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:08.400
our department.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:12.310
Should we take from the rich and
give to the poor, for example.

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:15.010
That's philosophy
department stuff.

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:19.650
Economists redefine
themselves in the 20th century

00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:21.160
as technicians.

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:23.745
Right, they say, should
we take from the rich

00:15:23.745 --> 00:15:24.620
and give to the poor.

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:27.350
That's not science,
that's philosophy.

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:29.520
That's ethics or morals.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:32.860
We are called in to talk about
is the economy functioning

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:38.570
well, and that functioning
means Pareto efficiency.

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:42.130
So I think that the economics
departments of the world

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:47.370
became less philosophical, less
moral in their orientation,

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:50.630
less interested in
how people behave.

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:52.480
They had this
mathematical framework,

00:15:52.480 --> 00:15:55.470
which had nothing about
people except that there

00:15:55.470 --> 00:15:57.760
are relentlessly selfish.

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:02.750
They then dragged out of
Adam Smith, who in 1776 wrote

00:16:02.750 --> 00:16:05.490
the classic of all time
in economics, the book,

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:06.950
"The Wealth of Nations."

00:16:06.950 --> 00:16:08.410
And there is a
quote they pull out

00:16:08.410 --> 00:16:13.310
one place in this book
where Adam Smith seems

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:18.650
to think that completely selfish
behavior within the limits

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:24.720
of a market economy that upholds
property rights is optimal.

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:26.550
He said something
like, I'm trying

00:16:26.550 --> 00:16:28.040
to remember the
exact quote, but he

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:33.900
said, "It's not to the
beneficence of the providers

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:37.140
of food that I get my dinner.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:40.420
The Baker, the brewer,
and the butcher

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:45.340
provide my dinner, because of
my paying them for what they do,

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:47.310
not out of any concern for me."

00:16:47.310 --> 00:16:50.650
And then Adam Smith went
on to say, you know,

00:16:50.650 --> 00:16:53.940
I get more from
those selfish people

00:16:53.940 --> 00:16:57.080
than I get from all the social
reformers of the world who

00:16:57.080 --> 00:16:58.520
don't seem to make
any difference.

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:00.960
That's all talk.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:04.640
That was a very loose
quote of Adam Smith.

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:05.640
But you know what?

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:07.640
These are extreme views.

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:10.829
And even Adam Smith
didn't believe that,

00:17:10.829 --> 00:17:13.510
because if you look in
other parts of his work,

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:17.530
he wrote another book in 1759
called "The Theory of Moral

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:18.780
Sentiments."

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:23.599
And in that book, he said
that people are not selfish.

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:25.579
They have some aspects
of selfishness,

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:30.080
but they're inherently
social creatures.

00:17:30.080 --> 00:17:33.740
Very interesting book,
his 1759 book, by the way.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:37.310
Vilfredo Pareto who
named Pareto optimality,

00:17:37.310 --> 00:17:39.340
himself didn't believe it.

00:17:39.340 --> 00:17:41.280
In fact, he dropped
out of economics,

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:43.530
and he spent the last
30 years of his life

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:47.950
as a sociologist trying
to understand society.

00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:51.690
I think that there is something
wrong with this theory.

00:17:51.690 --> 00:17:56.130
In 1918-- you see I have a
long time frame of history.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:18:02.050
I read these old ideas, and I
find it's useful to do that.

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:05.190
Go back 100 or 200
years, they have

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:07.200
ideas that we've forgotten.

00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:10.540
Professor Irving Fisher
at Yale University

00:18:10.540 --> 00:18:13.400
said that this whole
thing about utility

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:17.460
that economists talk
about, it's not right.

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:19.930
People don't maximize
their utility.

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:24.570
The word utility goes back to
the philosopher Jeremy Bentham

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:29.010
who said all philosophy
should be oriented toward,

00:18:29.010 --> 00:18:32.630
all morality should be
oriented toward utility.

00:18:32.630 --> 00:18:38.630
But utility, he said, meant
something like the human well

00:18:38.630 --> 00:18:41.850
being, human fulfilment.

00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:44.960
Irving Fisher said, that's
not what people maximize.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:49.070
They maximize, he said we
need another word for it.

00:18:49.070 --> 00:18:51.780
And he couldn't figure out
a really good word for,

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:54.030
it's not in a language,
so he coined one.

00:18:54.030 --> 00:18:56.770
And he said it's wantability.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:19:00.100
What you maximize
is not your utility,

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:05.110
it's what you want at the moment
that you make the purchase.

00:19:05.110 --> 00:19:09.750
That term, by the way
I love Google Trends,

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:12.740
Google Ngrams has changed
my life, because I always

00:19:12.740 --> 00:19:14.740
look up any idea.

00:19:14.740 --> 00:19:17.890
So I looked up wantability
on Google Ngrams,

00:19:17.890 --> 00:19:22.900
and I find his word did
not exist before 1918.

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:26.410
It exploded into usage
for the next 20 years,

00:19:26.410 --> 00:19:29.210
and then has exponentially
decayed since then.

00:19:32.210 --> 00:19:38.460
Now if you teach micro
theory in a university,

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:40.860
it's kind of a
difficult assignment,

00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:43.590
because it's supposed to be some
classical theory that everyone

00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:44.534
should know.

00:19:44.534 --> 00:19:46.200
And it's a little bit
depressing to have

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:47.820
to teach this old stuff.

00:19:47.820 --> 00:19:51.560
So nobody's really interested,
oh, I'm exaggerating.

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:55.000
But you'll teach the fundamental
theorem of welfare economics

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:01.180
with reverence and never come
back to distortions in it.

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:03.360
Now here what
we're talking about

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:04.650
is a phishing equilibrium.

00:20:04.650 --> 00:20:09.670
I think the simplest example,
because you've likely

00:20:09.670 --> 00:20:12.460
already heard of it, but
it's a very minor example,

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:16.980
but I'll start with this, is
the candy bars at the checkout

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:18.830
counter.

00:20:18.830 --> 00:20:21.280
Have you ever noticed
at a grocery store

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:22.970
when you go to the
checkout, you're

00:20:22.970 --> 00:20:26.130
standing in line
waiting to, now it

00:20:26.130 --> 00:20:27.750
might be a
computerized checkout,

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:30.820
but it would be still
standing in line for a while,

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:33.670
they have candy
bars right there.

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:36.410
So why is this?

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:40.080
Well, about 30 years ago some
social reformers and thought

00:20:40.080 --> 00:20:42.830
leaders decided to
make a case about this.

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:45.140
You know why they
put them there.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:48.640
It's because you don't go to
the grocery store intending

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:51.840
to buy candy bars, and
in fact, you probably

00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:54.580
have an idea that I'm
not going to buy that.

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:58.360
But now they put them right in
front of you at the worst time,

00:20:58.360 --> 00:20:59.960
right at the end of
your shopping trip

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:02.040
when you're standing
there in line.

00:21:02.040 --> 00:21:06.390
Moreover, many people go to
the store with young children.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:10.340
Now you've been shopping for 45
minutes, they're getting tired,

00:21:10.340 --> 00:21:12.320
and now you're putting
them in the experience

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:14.070
of standing in line.

00:21:14.070 --> 00:21:15.930
It's a most unpleasant ending.

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:19.620
So they know that
you're vulnerable,

00:21:19.620 --> 00:21:21.320
and they put it there.

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:24.037
Several decades ago
a number of stores

00:21:24.037 --> 00:21:25.620
announced that they
would not do that,

00:21:25.620 --> 00:21:28.810
because there seemed to be a
public reaction against it.

00:21:28.810 --> 00:21:30.950
However, if you
look now at stores,

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:34.226
it's all happening, it's all
back, the candy bars are back.

00:21:34.226 --> 00:21:36.060
And my colleague
George points out

00:21:36.060 --> 00:21:39.290
that the children's candy
is put at children's eye

00:21:39.290 --> 00:21:41.720
level in the store.

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:43.900
So this is just
illustrating what I

00:21:43.900 --> 00:21:45.850
mean by a phishing equilibrium.

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:51.590
Imagine that you took a job
as a manager of a supermarket.

00:21:51.590 --> 00:21:53.290
Do you think you would do this?

00:21:53.290 --> 00:21:55.290
I've pointed out that
you are in a sense

00:21:55.290 --> 00:21:59.280
exploiting your customers by
putting candy bars right there.

00:21:59.280 --> 00:22:03.100
It's almost evil, but it's not.

00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:05.950
The outrage has passed,
it had its moment,

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:08.860
and now it's now it's faded.

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:11.390
And so, would you do it?

00:22:11.390 --> 00:22:16.290
Well, the grocery
store business happens

00:22:16.290 --> 00:22:17.950
to be a highly competitive.

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.820
It's not a mostly
innovative business.

00:22:20.820 --> 00:22:23.000
There's a lot of competitors.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.410
There's no organizational
slack, which gives you freedom.

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:29.310
If you became a manager
of a grocery store,

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:31.940
you would probably become
very quickly conscious

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:36.220
that other grocery stores go
out of business all the time.

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:39.220
Your profit margin
is something like 2%.

00:22:39.220 --> 00:22:42.310
You can't monkey around
too much without risking

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:44.300
the whole enterprise.

00:22:44.300 --> 00:22:47.740
So you probably would
do it, too, right?

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:51.050
The other thing is
that managers learn

00:22:51.050 --> 00:22:55.010
that the best way to
manage if in doubt, imitate

00:22:55.010 --> 00:22:56.540
what other people are doing.

00:22:56.540 --> 00:22:59.350
You assume that
they've experimented.

00:22:59.350 --> 00:23:01.950
It's costly for
me to experiment.

00:23:01.950 --> 00:23:04.760
Apparently, everyone puts
candy bars at the checkout,

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:06.740
so I will do that too.

00:23:06.740 --> 00:23:13.740
Now I've picked a very
minor example about this.

00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:16.870
What we did in our book is
also somewhat similar to what

00:23:16.870 --> 00:23:18.400
Vance Packard and
others have done

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:21.410
is just give a lot of examples.

00:23:21.410 --> 00:23:25.790
Our examples come from all
different times in history.

00:23:25.790 --> 00:23:32.332
Some of them-- let me just
give you a couple of examples.

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:38.300
One of them is, there's a
book by Natasha Schull called

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:42.280
"Addiction by Design," and
it's about slot machines.

00:23:42.280 --> 00:23:44.440
It's really about
machine gambling.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:49.880
She points out that gambling
has changed in recent decades,

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:52.970
and it's become more
machine oriented.

00:23:52.970 --> 00:23:56.970
That is slot machines are rising
as a share of total profits

00:23:56.970 --> 00:23:58.750
for gambling enterprises.

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:00.460
And why is that?

00:24:00.460 --> 00:24:03.000
Well, she presents
an analysis saying

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:07.440
that people are more
vulnerable toward addiction

00:24:07.440 --> 00:24:10.580
when they are under the
control of a machine.

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:12.144
So gambling is less and less.

00:24:12.144 --> 00:24:14.560
I'm going to have some friends
over, and we'll play cards,

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:19.520
we'll play a little poker, which
would be a social environment.

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:25.740
When they first discovered
slot machines in the 1890s,

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:29.400
slot machines were found to be
addictive to a small percent

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:30.950
of the population.

00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:33.030
They seemed to
just keep doing it.

00:24:33.030 --> 00:24:35.290
Have you ever noticed
these people in a casino?

00:24:39.190 --> 00:24:43.540
I think it has something
to do with a brain bug.

00:24:43.540 --> 00:24:46.580
Another book, I like
books, so I'm mentioning,

00:24:46.580 --> 00:24:50.800
there is a book by
neuroscientists Dean Buonomano

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:53.130
called "Brain Bugs."

00:24:53.130 --> 00:24:57.600
His premise is that the
brain is a computer,

00:24:57.600 --> 00:25:00.680
and it has a built
in program as well as

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:05.450
adjustments that you add as a
part of your education later.

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:08.530
But the built in
program has bugs in it.

00:25:08.530 --> 00:25:14.240
It's a product of Darwinian
evolution, but only incomplete.

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:17.350
Evolution is much slower
than computer programs

00:25:17.350 --> 00:25:20.900
are and writing code, and
so there are lots of bugs.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:22.700
The book details all the bugs.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:25.630
And I think it's
interesting reading.

00:25:25.630 --> 00:25:28.420
It's a funny perspective
to take on yourself.

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:31.850
Well, apparently this
slot machine addiction

00:25:31.850 --> 00:25:34.050
has something to do
with a bug in the reward

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:38.250
system in the brain that
for some people encourages

00:25:38.250 --> 00:25:39.403
repetitive behavior.

00:25:42.370 --> 00:25:44.760
I used to code in Fortran,
so I kind of think of it

00:25:44.760 --> 00:25:46.786
as being stuck in a do loop.

00:25:46.786 --> 00:25:48.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:48.970 --> 00:25:54.040
So according to Natasha Schull,
researchers on slot machines

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:58.970
have tried to figure out what
makes for a successful slot

00:25:58.970 --> 00:25:59.960
machine.

00:25:59.960 --> 00:26:05.270
And they found out that I
guess the optimal interval

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:08.890
between gambles is
3 and 1/2 seconds.

00:26:08.890 --> 00:26:11.720
So they try to make it,
that's because it's somehow

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:14.780
the reward
neuroscientists have found

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:18.970
tends to come at the
moment of anticipation.

00:26:18.970 --> 00:26:22.940
The work of Wolfram Schultz, so
the dopamine system sends out

00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:25.240
signals the moment
you think I've just

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:28.377
placed a bet I'm hopeful.

00:26:28.377 --> 00:26:30.710
And then that dies out after
a certain interval of time.

00:26:30.710 --> 00:26:33.220
So if you want it to
be optimally addicting,

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:35.030
you have to make it
easy for the person

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:38.149
to keep playing bets
at that interval.

00:26:38.149 --> 00:26:40.440
So they've eliminated the
crank that used to pull down.

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:44.120
That seemed to interfere
with the optimal frequency.

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:46.544
And another thing
they've learned

00:26:46.544 --> 00:26:47.960
is that people are
trying to stop.

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:51.260
They're sitting there thinking,
you know I've lost $25 already,

00:26:51.260 --> 00:26:52.250
maybe I should stop.

00:26:52.250 --> 00:26:54.450
But they can't quite
bring themselves to stop.

00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:56.500
Well, they've discovered
through research

00:26:56.500 --> 00:27:02.690
that people who are
gambling machine addicts

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:05.610
tend to stop if there's anything
interrupting the flow of just

00:27:05.610 --> 00:27:07.280
pushing, pushing, pushing.

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:10.980
It used to be that coins
would come out when you won,

00:27:10.980 --> 00:27:15.000
and they'd make a loud noise
and a big spectacle and great.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.460
But the problem is that
it disrupted the flow,

00:27:17.460 --> 00:27:20.054
and many people would pack
up and leave at that point.

00:27:20.054 --> 00:27:21.970
You don't want them to
pack up and leave right

00:27:21.970 --> 00:27:24.270
when they've won something.

00:27:24.270 --> 00:27:28.090
So they now substitute a
synthesised digital sound

00:27:28.090 --> 00:27:31.210
of coins falling, so it
won't break the rhythm

00:27:31.210 --> 00:27:34.090
of your keeping on betting.

00:27:34.090 --> 00:27:35.820
They've also
discovered that people

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:40.310
are a little bit ashamed to be
sitting at the slot machine,

00:27:40.310 --> 00:27:43.850
so they try to find a nook where
they are away from other people

00:27:43.850 --> 00:27:45.230
observing them too much.

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:48.810
But they have a social component
to the gambling still has that.

00:27:48.810 --> 00:27:51.580
They like to see the
excitement of the Casino.

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:53.510
So you optimize
the structure, so

00:27:53.510 --> 00:27:56.550
that they have the slight
sense that they're hiding

00:27:56.550 --> 00:27:58.830
in privacy with this machine.

00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:01.822
Anyway, you get the idea.

00:28:01.822 --> 00:28:04.280
I don't how you people, you're
not doing anything like this

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:06.490
here, right?

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:08.080
I hope not.

00:28:08.080 --> 00:28:12.470
But even so, if you can
imagine taking a job designing

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:16.150
slot machines, you
might be affected

00:28:16.150 --> 00:28:18.600
to do the same sort of thing.

00:28:18.600 --> 00:28:20.710
Let me give you another example.

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:24.920
Coca-Cola is the most
famous beverage ever.

00:28:24.920 --> 00:28:26.170
Why?

00:28:26.170 --> 00:28:29.190
Now I've always wondered this,
because I never particularly

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:30.250
liked it.

00:28:30.250 --> 00:28:32.050
I don't dislike it either.

00:28:32.050 --> 00:28:34.320
I mean, it's just,
Yeah, it's fine.

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:37.520
But how did it get to be so big?

00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:40.800
Well, it's a testimony
to marketing.

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:43.240
And the people at
Coca-Cola had a belief

00:28:43.240 --> 00:28:49.450
that-- I'm relying this on
a book "Salt, Sugar, Fat"

00:28:49.450 --> 00:28:51.460
by Michael Moss.

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:54.470
It was a best seller a year ago.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:56.080
According to his
history of this,

00:28:56.080 --> 00:28:57.970
the Coca-Cola
people were acutely

00:28:57.970 --> 00:29:01.200
aware of the
importance of attaching

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:05.430
memories of good moments
to their beverage.

00:29:05.430 --> 00:29:09.130
And they would try
to use advertising

00:29:09.130 --> 00:29:13.730
to make a connection,
so that later on you

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:16.260
would just think Coca-Cola,
it's great, it's good.

00:29:16.260 --> 00:29:18.280
Somehow, I feel good.

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:21.360
Now I think that what
those people did was

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:26.520
they did something that
was an anticipation

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:29.960
of modern neuroscience.

00:29:29.960 --> 00:29:32.030
And that is that
neuroscience now

00:29:32.030 --> 00:29:35.110
says that the human
mind as a computer

00:29:35.110 --> 00:29:39.260
has a filing system for
memories that attach emotions

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:40.490
to each memory.

00:29:40.490 --> 00:29:44.890
So I think it's a good idea to
put an emotion on every memory.

00:29:44.890 --> 00:29:48.790
It's not a human idea,
that's an evolutionary idea.

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:52.770
It's like having a file cabinet
with different colored folders,

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:56.140
and important stuff you
put in a red folder,

00:29:56.140 --> 00:29:58.315
so it attaches an emotion.

00:29:58.315 --> 00:30:00.440
Another is starting to see
that the brain is really

00:30:00.440 --> 00:30:01.830
structured that way.

00:30:01.830 --> 00:30:05.820
So for example, you
have the amygdala,

00:30:05.820 --> 00:30:10.300
which is somewhere in here, that
attaches emotions to memory.

00:30:10.300 --> 00:30:14.015
The right amygdala specializes
in fear, for example.

