00:32:26.990 --> 00:32:29.880
Anyway I'm supposed to wrap up.

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:32.297
What I wanted to do
is get to what is our,

00:32:32.297 --> 00:32:33.880
I don't know if I
presented this well,

00:32:33.880 --> 00:32:41.340
but I wanted to get
to the idea that we

00:32:41.340 --> 00:32:44.560
have about why we are
as successful as we

00:32:44.560 --> 00:32:49.120
seem to be in this country.

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:52.840
What is our core
reason for success.

00:32:52.840 --> 00:32:58.040
A view has enveloped that it
is because of our free market

00:32:58.040 --> 00:33:01.160
institutions that
encourage entrepreneurs.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:07.940
That's certainly partly right,
but is that the only thing.

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:13.270
Or should we, it seems like
we might be oversimplifying

00:33:13.270 --> 00:33:16.690
to give quite so much.

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:20.950
So why is America
a great country?

00:33:20.950 --> 00:33:23.420
I have a couple of suggested
readings on this, which

00:33:23.420 --> 00:33:27.120
you can find on Google Books.

00:33:27.120 --> 00:33:30.006
And I'm so thankful to Google,
which gives me so much help.

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:36.570
In 1780, I think the year
was, Benjamin Franklin wrote

00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:40.020
a short article to be
published in Europe.

00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:43.200
And the title of the
article was "Information

00:33:43.200 --> 00:33:48.600
for People Contemplating
Repairing to America."

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:54.280
It was a description of
America in 1780 for Europeans.

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:59.730
And in that description
he said, "Be warned.

00:33:59.730 --> 00:34:02.620
Your erudition will do
you nothing in America.

00:34:02.620 --> 00:34:05.410
The Americans are
very practical people,

00:34:05.410 --> 00:34:07.740
and they want to see results.

00:34:07.740 --> 00:34:11.770
If you are a skilled
workman of some sort, fine,

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:13.719
come to America
and you'll do well.

00:34:13.719 --> 00:34:18.620
But if you're on an aristocrat
or an artist or a philosopher,

00:34:18.620 --> 00:34:20.633
don't come."

00:34:20.633 --> 00:34:21.924
That's something about America.

00:34:21.924 --> 00:34:24.480
It reflects the kind
of people who came here

00:34:24.480 --> 00:34:26.800
and the attitude that developed.

00:34:26.800 --> 00:34:29.750
The other one you my read
is Alexis de Tocqueville

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:32.880
who has a lot to say
about American character.

00:34:32.880 --> 00:34:37.040
The point is that this country
is a success partly because

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:41.330
of free markets, but also
because of civil society.

00:34:41.330 --> 00:34:43.830
And it's actions
that people have

00:34:43.830 --> 00:34:49.520
taken to prevent the phishing
equilibrium from dominating.

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:55.929
So it's not just individual acts
of ethics or acts of concern.

00:34:55.929 --> 00:34:59.950
We can exhibit, for example, the
founder of Ogilvy and Mather,

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:03.800
the ad agency,
Ogilvy in the 1940s

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:07.870
announced that his company would
not take on any more cigarette

00:35:07.870 --> 00:35:09.770
advertisements.

00:35:09.770 --> 00:35:12.060
I think that if you read
the medical literature

00:35:12.060 --> 00:35:15.340
in the 20th century,
it started to become

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:20.310
like I have a hunch cigarette
smoking is bad for you by 1915.

00:35:20.310 --> 00:35:26.460
By 1940 it still wasn't
proven, but someone

00:35:26.460 --> 00:35:29.280
who read the literature would
probably say, this is it,

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:30.770
I'm not smoking.

00:35:30.770 --> 00:35:33.630
It looked pretty bad.

00:35:33.630 --> 00:35:38.350
So that's when Ogilvy pulled
out of a cigarette advertising.

00:35:38.350 --> 00:35:41.390
But it didn't have no
effect on the outcome,

00:35:41.390 --> 00:35:44.370
because somebody else
just goes right back in.

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:46.360
There's a profit to be made.

00:35:46.360 --> 00:35:48.960
And there was a profit
to be made from phishing.

00:35:48.960 --> 00:35:56.420
The cigarette companies tried
a strategy of sowing confusion

00:35:56.420 --> 00:35:57.510
about tobacco.

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:00.670
They found that the president
of the University of Michigan,

00:36:00.670 --> 00:36:04.430
Little, was a
skeptic and a smoker.

00:36:04.430 --> 00:36:06.070
He loved his smoking.

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:08.010
And they got him to
say that no one has

00:36:08.010 --> 00:36:10.820
proved at a statistically
significant level

00:36:10.820 --> 00:36:13.090
that smoking is harmful.

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:14.770
Maybe he was right,
or maybe they

00:36:14.770 --> 00:36:18.370
didn't understand causality
well enough to prove it.

00:36:18.370 --> 00:36:23.450
But basically, it was a feint
to try to get people confused,

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:26.130
and it was for profit.

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:27.830
So what we really
need is somebody

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:31.630
who will stand above
the profit incentive

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:35.800
and will do something to try
to limit profit opportunities

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:40.610
for things that we can't stand.

00:36:40.610 --> 00:36:42.610
And I've been
concluding my talks

00:36:42.610 --> 00:36:48.340
by just giving a few examples
of heroes who sort of started

00:36:48.340 --> 00:36:49.250
social movements.

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:53.726
And there are a
great many heroes.

00:36:56.510 --> 00:37:01.280
What I've been doing as a game,
I've done a book tour for this.

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:02.520
I'll try it here, too.

00:37:02.520 --> 00:37:06.680
The game is I'll give you
some names of famous people

00:37:06.680 --> 00:37:10.500
who upheld morality in
business and ask you

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:13.230
if there's anyone
here who can tell me

00:37:13.230 --> 00:37:15.225
who they are by their name.

00:37:15.225 --> 00:37:16.850
Now, if you read our
book, you'll know,

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:19.180
but that's cheating.

00:37:19.180 --> 00:37:22.550
So let me start with
Florence Kelley.

00:37:22.550 --> 00:37:25.830
Anyone heard of her?

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:28.560
As anticipated, no one has.

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:35.790
Florence Kelley in 1899 set up
the National Consumers League,

00:37:35.790 --> 00:37:40.660
which tested products for
safety and put a white label,

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:42.840
this was a nonprofit,
a white label

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:48.380
on products that were safe.

00:37:48.380 --> 00:37:52.300
William Henry Merrill, now
this is not the Merrill Lynch

00:37:52.300 --> 00:37:54.320
Merrill.

00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:57.140
Again no one.

00:37:57.140 --> 00:37:59.930
In 1893 he was an
electrician who

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:03.510
was asked to inspect the
electricity at the Chicago

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:06.500
World's Fair palace
of electricity.

00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:08.710
It was really an
exciting display

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:11.190
of what things were going
to come through electricity,

00:38:11.190 --> 00:38:12.350
but it was unsafe.

00:38:12.350 --> 00:38:14.780
Their wiring wasn't
right, so he decided

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:20.010
to set up a nonprofit called
United Laboratories or UL,

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:24.090
and they would put their
mark on safe products.

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:27.210
This worked, because it
made it impossible to phish.

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:31.080
The word got out, don't
buy if it doesn't say UL,

00:38:31.080 --> 00:38:34.100
and that stopped certain
kinds of phishing.

00:38:34.100 --> 00:38:37.270
By the way, UL made
a corporate change

00:38:37.270 --> 00:38:43.100
just as Google has in this month
in 2012, it went for profit.

00:38:43.100 --> 00:38:45.470
I believe it's still
doing the same business,

00:38:45.470 --> 00:38:50.430
and it's the same socially
conscious business.

00:38:50.430 --> 00:38:56.910
Another hero, Alice Lakey
and Harvey Washington Wiley.

00:38:56.910 --> 00:38:59.894
OK, 0.

00:38:59.894 --> 00:39:00.810
I've done this before.

00:39:00.810 --> 00:39:03.500
I hope I'm not offending you.

00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:09.120
What these people did is made
a public campaign about drugs.

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:14.480
They argued that
as of 1900, most

00:39:14.480 --> 00:39:18.130
drugs that you could buy in
a drug store were fraudulent.

00:39:18.130 --> 00:39:21.050
There was something
like Swaim's Panacea.

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:21.850
What is that?

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:24.700
First of all, it claimed
to cure any illness.

00:39:24.700 --> 00:39:26.610
There's something
wrong about that.

00:39:26.610 --> 00:39:28.630
And then secondly, they
tested what was in it.

00:39:28.630 --> 00:39:31.490
And it was just ordinary
household flavoring.

00:39:31.490 --> 00:39:34.140
It was a complete fraud.

00:39:34.140 --> 00:39:36.940
And they said, but
what's to stop a business

00:39:36.940 --> 00:39:38.420
from doing that?

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:40.650
When they advertised
in magazines,

00:39:40.650 --> 00:39:43.050
they're telling the
magazine, don't criticize

00:39:43.050 --> 00:39:44.190
us or we'll pull our ad.

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:46.070
So there's no incentive
for the advertising.

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:47.760
Well, maybe there
was some incentive.

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:51.700
But to do a testing lab
and to do-- so anyway,

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:54.280
they got the government to
create the Food and Drug

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:57.450
Administration in 1906.

00:39:57.450 --> 00:40:01.392
Another hero, Stuart Chase
and Frederick Schlink.

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:08.610
OK, Stuart, they wrote
a book in the 1920s

00:40:08.610 --> 00:40:10.160
called "Your Money's Worth."

00:40:10.160 --> 00:40:14.480
And they said the FDA is not
enough, because they're still

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:15.810
monkeying with you.

00:40:15.810 --> 00:40:17.980
They said, take the
example of toothpaste.

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:19.492
I'm quoting from their book.

00:40:19.492 --> 00:40:20.950
"We go to a drug
store, and there's

00:40:20.950 --> 00:40:22.710
10 different brands
of toothpaste,

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:25.280
and they all make health claims.

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:28.572
Maybe they're all safe,
the FDA has tested them,

00:40:28.572 --> 00:40:30.030
but what about
those health claims?

00:40:30.030 --> 00:40:31.830
How does anyone know?"

00:40:31.830 --> 00:40:34.110
So they said, "We need
a regular publication

00:40:34.110 --> 00:40:35.540
that tests products."

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.530
That was done in 1936.

00:40:37.530 --> 00:40:40.230
That's Consumer Reports.

00:40:40.230 --> 00:40:43.240
Finally, one more
here, Ben Bernanke.

00:40:43.240 --> 00:40:45.142
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:45.142 --> 00:40:46.600
Well, I guess I
don't have to tell.

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:48.790
But I think that he's a hero.

00:40:48.790 --> 00:40:52.160
It's not a for profit
operation that he led,

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:55.060
it was the Federal Reserve.

00:40:55.060 --> 00:41:02.030
And he probably prevented
another Great Depression,

00:41:02.030 --> 00:41:05.840
which was based on
a loss of confidence

00:41:05.840 --> 00:41:09.400
and a tumult within
the financial sector.

00:41:09.400 --> 00:41:11.380
Controversial
things that he did.

00:41:14.620 --> 00:41:27.240
So anyway, that's my view, our
view expressed in this book.

00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:30.420
I say that our book is,
I'm already controversial.

00:41:30.420 --> 00:41:34.170
I may have offended some of you.

00:41:34.170 --> 00:41:38.960
It's considered unpatriotic to,
it seems considered unpatriotic

00:41:38.960 --> 00:41:42.430
here in America
especially to say anything

00:41:42.430 --> 00:41:45.510
in favor of any
kinds of regulation.

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:47.390
But I wanted to
add that I'm not,

00:41:47.390 --> 00:41:50.320
there's a tendency to
think about free markets

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:52.020
versus government.

00:41:52.020 --> 00:41:54.360
I'm not thinking so
much about government.

00:41:54.360 --> 00:42:00.250
Those heroes I gave you were
outside of the government

00:42:00.250 --> 00:42:03.250
except for Ben Bernanke.

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:06.750
The idea of civil
society is a society

00:42:06.750 --> 00:42:12.610
with people who have
a sense of community,

00:42:12.610 --> 00:42:15.380
a sense of responsibility
for what goes on.

00:42:15.380 --> 00:42:19.680
They tend to view the government
as just people we hire to do

00:42:19.680 --> 00:42:23.580
what we want as a community.

00:42:23.580 --> 00:42:27.230
They don't allow
themselves to be

00:42:27.230 --> 00:42:31.570
captured by propaganda,
because of their sense

00:42:31.570 --> 00:42:32.940
of responsibility.

00:42:32.940 --> 00:42:36.230
And they tend to
be educated people,

00:42:36.230 --> 00:42:40.670
and they take the
effort to get knowledge.

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:44.330
So that's what this
book is a plea for.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:48.780
Now how this fits into
Google with its big data

00:42:48.780 --> 00:42:51.002
and its Cloud.

00:42:51.002 --> 00:42:52.460
There's so many
things you do here,

00:42:52.460 --> 00:42:56.700
I find it hard to summarize
what I would think.

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:58.840
But it seems to me
that there is already

00:42:58.840 --> 00:43:03.110
a moral spirit at Google as I
was saying at the beginning.

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:07.320
And I think you have
more organizational slack

00:43:07.320 --> 00:43:10.080
than a grocery store does.

00:43:10.080 --> 00:43:14.630
That means you can
philosophize about the long run

00:43:14.630 --> 00:43:16.550
future of this organization.

00:43:16.550 --> 00:43:20.140
And you can take steps that
are maybe costly in terms

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:25.050
of profits today, but in the
long run are the right things

00:43:25.050 --> 00:43:30.490
to do, and may not even be
in the long run crossly.

00:43:30.490 --> 00:43:33.615
I'll stop with that and
open this up to questions.

00:43:36.345 --> 00:43:39.255
