Thank you.

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:49.020
AUDIENCE: How can behavioral
economic theory influence

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:51.640
like what's taught
in universities?

00:43:51.640 --> 00:43:53.040
Will it take over?

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:56.847
Will rational actor
eventually not be taught?

00:43:56.847 --> 00:43:58.680
ROBERT SHILLER: Well,
I think it will always

00:43:58.680 --> 00:44:01.250
be taught, because it's
actually a useful thing

00:44:01.250 --> 00:44:04.140
to the rational actor,
and the idea of Pareto

00:44:04.140 --> 00:44:07.066
optimality is worth
talking about.

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:15.950
But the problem with
the economics profession

00:44:15.950 --> 00:44:20.340
now is that it like other
academic disciplines,

00:44:20.340 --> 00:44:24.330
they get separated and isolated.

00:44:24.330 --> 00:44:28.320
And it develops a sort
of departmental inertia.

00:44:28.320 --> 00:44:29.830
Here's what happens.

00:44:29.830 --> 00:44:32.330
You become the
economics department.

00:44:32.330 --> 00:44:33.550
Now in your research.

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:34.610
Now you're a community.

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:39.920
There's a social
tendency, tribal tendency.

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:43.740
You start to view the psychology
department as arrival,

00:44:43.740 --> 00:44:45.695
arrival for university funding.

00:44:48.700 --> 00:44:53.040
And moreover, you start
developing a brand.

00:44:53.040 --> 00:44:57.300
So you attract PhD
students, let's say,

00:44:57.300 --> 00:45:01.610
who wanted to become
mathematical economist.

00:45:01.610 --> 00:45:02.760
So what do you do?

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:05.280
You can't say, well, we've
changed our mind this year,

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:07.300
we're going to teach
you psychology.

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:08.924
That's not what they want.

00:45:08.924 --> 00:45:09.840
They want to get jobs.

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:11.214
It becomes all routinized.

00:45:11.214 --> 00:45:12.630
They want to get
jobs, so you have

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:16.640
to teach them what
will get them a job

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:21.140
in a conventional
economics department.

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:22.900
And also there's
this pressure to be

00:45:22.900 --> 00:45:27.450
at the frontier that means
that you don't have time

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:29.550
to read other things.

00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:31.800
So you're struggling
so hard to get

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:35.370
at the pinnacle of some
mathematical discourse.

00:45:35.370 --> 00:45:37.230
You just run out of time.

00:45:37.230 --> 00:45:39.360
By the way, there's
another interesting book,

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:43.580
which just came out by
Gillian Tett called "The Silo

00:45:43.580 --> 00:45:48.490
Effect," which argues this more
generally for corporations.

00:45:48.490 --> 00:45:52.300
Maybe this is an argument
against Alphabet, by the way.

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:54.920
They said, Larry
Page said it would

00:45:54.920 --> 00:46:01.710
be neater and more incentivizing
or accountable or something

00:46:01.710 --> 00:46:05.970
if we divide Google
into a separate unit

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:07.850
with separate CEOs.

00:46:07.850 --> 00:46:11.730
But what Gillian Tett
says is that can produce

00:46:11.730 --> 00:46:15.160
a bad outcome of too
much specialization,

00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:17.900
and then also a kind
of culture developing

00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:20.020
in each one of
these units that's

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:23.550
kind of antagonistic to
other cultures in a sense

00:46:23.550 --> 00:46:27.790
that if you defy the
norms of your tribe,

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:32.420
you will be unpatriotic
in some sense.

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:34.665
So I haven't finished
reading her book,

00:46:34.665 --> 00:46:38.190
bu it sounds like it's a
really important topic.

00:46:38.190 --> 00:46:41.810
And it accounts for the kind
of errors that are commonly

00:46:41.810 --> 00:46:46.020
made in modern society.

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:49.700
AUDIENCE: So because of some
of this momentum in economics

00:46:49.700 --> 00:46:51.750
like forgetting
graduate students

00:46:51.750 --> 00:46:56.350
that want to do
mathematical economics,

00:46:56.350 --> 00:46:59.110
is there any math associated
with some of these more

00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:00.029
behavioral approaches?

00:47:00.029 --> 00:47:01.070
ROBERT SHILLER: Oh, Yeah.

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:02.040
AUDIENCE: Can it?

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:03.940
ROBERT SHILLER: Yeah,
behavioral economics

00:47:03.940 --> 00:47:05.910
has some mathematics in it.

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:11.340
Right, I mean you can ask
what is it that people do,

00:47:11.340 --> 00:47:14.110
and there can be, there's
mathematical psychology.

00:47:14.110 --> 00:47:15.980
But the problem
is it doesn't have

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:20.510
the elegance of general
equilibrium economic theory.

00:47:20.510 --> 00:47:24.160
And people who
want to understand

00:47:24.160 --> 00:47:27.510
how did this whole
set of prices get set.

00:47:27.510 --> 00:47:29.190
Where did they come from?

00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:33.340
Free markets generate them,
but where and how and why?

00:47:33.340 --> 00:47:37.700
That incline, there's a sort
of wishful thinking bias that

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:39.870
develops if you are a theorist.

00:47:39.870 --> 00:47:43.260
You kind of hope this
expected utility maximization

00:47:43.260 --> 00:47:47.600
theory is right, because it
makes for a nice modeling.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:50.310
If you look at what
psychologists say,

00:47:50.310 --> 00:47:52.220
it's just too messy.

00:47:52.220 --> 00:47:55.380
And you can't say whether
we've-- parade or optimality is

00:47:55.380 --> 00:47:58.770
a nice concept, because it
gives you a clear conclusion.

00:47:58.770 --> 00:48:01.572
But if people are
psychological animals,

00:48:01.572 --> 00:48:03.530
how do we know that we've
made them better off?

00:48:03.530 --> 00:48:06.720
I'll give you an example
that Daniel Kahneman, who

00:48:06.720 --> 00:48:09.300
wrote a nice book,
"Thinking Fast and Slow."

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:11.760
He's a psychologist
interested in economics.

00:48:11.760 --> 00:48:15.770
But one thing he did is he
questioned whether we even

00:48:15.770 --> 00:48:18.540
know our own happiness.

00:48:18.540 --> 00:48:20.720
You assume that people
are making purchases

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:22.300
to make themselves happy.

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:24.630
Do people know what
makes them happy?

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:26.880
So he did the
following experiment.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:29.840
He asked subjects
to thrust their hand

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:34.820
into a bowl of ice
water for 60 seconds.

00:48:34.820 --> 00:48:36.380
By the way, try that.

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:38.225
You won't like it.

00:48:38.225 --> 00:48:41.970
It gets really annoying.

00:48:41.970 --> 00:48:46.060
That was condition
A. Then condition B,

00:48:46.060 --> 00:48:49.670
he asked them to do that
again, but actually it's

00:48:49.670 --> 00:48:51.170
for 90 seconds.

00:48:51.170 --> 00:48:53.670
But he's got a little
temperature raiser

00:48:53.670 --> 00:48:57.280
in the bowl that raises the
temperature for the last 30

00:48:57.280 --> 00:49:00.180
seconds to something
more comfortable.

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:04.820
And then later asks which
did you like better A or B?

00:49:04.820 --> 00:49:08.630
Most people like B better.

00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:11.800
That's because,
apparently their memory

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:15.520
is affected by the improvement.

00:49:15.520 --> 00:49:19.850
It's been 70 seconds, now I'm
starting to feel OK again.

00:49:19.850 --> 00:49:22.470
But they were actually
in ice water longer.

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:27.070
So by some objective criteria,
they should have picked A,

00:49:27.070 --> 00:49:28.300
but they didn't.

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:30.920
So the question is
whether people even know

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:33.680
whether they're happy or not.

00:49:33.680 --> 00:49:35.220
It's a different view.

00:49:35.220 --> 00:49:39.570
It makes it harder to do
economics, because yeah,

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:43.930
the human brain is this
complicated interconnected

00:49:43.930 --> 00:49:45.410
calculating machine.

00:49:45.410 --> 00:49:47.180
What's good?

00:49:47.180 --> 00:49:48.880
I don't know what's good for it.

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:51.650
And if people don't know,
it just kind of leaves

00:49:51.650 --> 00:49:52.880
you inconclusive.

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:54.420
So economists won't like that.

00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:07.280
AUDIENCE: It's interesting
that your heroes were not

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:08.950
government people.

00:50:08.950 --> 00:50:12.000
And of course, the
defenders of pure--

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.210
ROBERT SHILLER: Ben Bernanke
was, but most weren't.

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:15.585
AUDIENCE: Your
free market theory

00:50:15.585 --> 00:50:17.920
would argue that the
most extreme would

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.250
say, oh well, we don't
need government regulation,

00:50:20.250 --> 00:50:25.410
because the markets will
pop up people like this

00:50:25.410 --> 00:50:29.480
where there's demand for them.

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:35.750
I'm curious about your
general views about that.

00:50:35.750 --> 00:50:38.500
And even professional
licensing, of course,

00:50:38.500 --> 00:50:41.470
Milton Friedman famously
argued that not even doctors

00:50:41.470 --> 00:50:43.200
and lawyers should be licensed.

00:50:43.200 --> 00:50:46.780
But I'm interested in
the latest phenomenon

00:50:46.780 --> 00:50:49.030
of this seems to be reviews.

00:50:49.030 --> 00:50:51.950
So Amazon has
reviews of products,

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:56.360
Uber, Airbnb both have
reviews of both sides

00:50:56.360 --> 00:50:59.240
of the transaction.

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:02.720
Google is trying to
get more reviews.

00:51:02.720 --> 00:51:06.570
I'm curious about your thoughts
about the review phenomenon.

00:51:06.570 --> 00:51:09.270
Obviously, it has
lots of problems,

00:51:09.270 --> 00:51:14.770
not just organized campaigns
to do biased reviews,

00:51:14.770 --> 00:51:18.100
but sort of the herd
instinct with reviews

00:51:18.100 --> 00:51:20.100
and lots of other things.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:24.410
Are reviews really the latest
of this heroic phenomenon

00:51:24.410 --> 00:51:28.620
or is it all just self
deception or what's going on

00:51:28.620 --> 00:51:32.300
with the whole review thing?

00:51:32.300 --> 00:51:34.910
ROBERT SHILLER: Well, you raise
a lot of interesting points.

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:37.610
Let me start with
Milton Friedman.

00:51:37.610 --> 00:51:44.120
In 1962 he wrote a book called
"Capitalism and Freedom" that

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:48.040
was actually an outgrowth of
an earlier work he'd done with,

00:51:48.040 --> 00:51:53.090
who was at, Kuznets on
occupational licensing.

00:51:53.090 --> 00:51:56.890
And in that book, he argued
that occupational licensing

00:51:56.890 --> 00:52:01.410
is merely an effort
by the practitioners

00:52:01.410 --> 00:52:03.890
to exclude competition.

00:52:03.890 --> 00:52:06.250
So here's what happens.

00:52:06.250 --> 00:52:11.650
The AMA goes to appear before
a medical licensing board

00:52:11.650 --> 00:52:15.390
and argues persuasively
that something has to be,

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:19.170
a practice has to be prohibited
unless it's licensed.

00:52:19.170 --> 00:52:21.870
But that in fact is
merely keeping others

00:52:21.870 --> 00:52:24.510
out of practicing.

00:52:24.510 --> 00:52:27.870
The outcome is that our
medical services are excellent,

00:52:27.870 --> 00:52:32.150
but there aren't enough of
them, and they're too expensive.

00:52:32.150 --> 00:52:35.810
He said that somehow the
community doesn't understand

00:52:35.810 --> 00:52:38.406
that, and so it's a doop.

00:52:38.406 --> 00:52:39.780
He's really talking
about it kind

00:52:39.780 --> 00:52:42.760
of manipulation and deception.

00:52:42.760 --> 00:52:44.800
But the problem
is, what would we

00:52:44.800 --> 00:52:49.980
do about not having any
licensure for doctors?

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:51.370
The problem is we
know that there

00:52:51.370 --> 00:52:53.370
is a lot of quack
medicine that could

00:52:53.370 --> 00:52:55.640
be sold to ignorant people.

00:52:55.640 --> 00:53:01.680
So maybe what he proposed
has never been adopted

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:03.600
by any country, I think.

00:53:03.600 --> 00:53:06.180
Any advanced country has
licensing for doctors.

00:53:06.180 --> 00:53:10.640
But another thing is I actually
like Milton Friedman and admire

00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:11.820
his works.

00:53:11.820 --> 00:53:13.650
What he actually
did with that book

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:17.930
was quite significant,
because within a few years

00:53:17.930 --> 00:53:22.620
of the publication of that book,
the first nurse practitioner

00:53:22.620 --> 00:53:28.260
program was started, or
a physician's assistant.

00:53:28.260 --> 00:53:30.710
What that did is
it really increased

00:53:30.710 --> 00:53:33.560
the supply of medical services.

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:39.030
The AMA back down and allowed
that a physicians assistant

00:53:39.030 --> 00:53:43.580
could practice in the
office of a licensed MD.

00:53:43.580 --> 00:53:46.730
The outcome of that
was the reduction

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:51.500
in the cost of medical
services and improved health.

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:55.020
So I think that the
idea that regulators

00:53:55.020 --> 00:53:58.300
can be captured
by the regulator,

00:53:58.300 --> 00:54:00.570
that the regulations don't
always serve the public

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:03.010
is correct.

00:54:03.010 --> 00:54:06.170
But that shouldn't
be taken as a blanket

00:54:06.170 --> 00:54:09.380
argument against regulation.

00:54:09.380 --> 00:54:13.250
The other thing you've asked is
about reviews on websites now

00:54:13.250 --> 00:54:16.290
that allow people to
see others comments.

00:54:16.290 --> 00:54:18.526
I think that is a
wonderful development.

00:54:18.526 --> 00:54:21.860
It used to be that--
our ability to shop

00:54:21.860 --> 00:54:23.990
has become so much better.

00:54:23.990 --> 00:54:25.680
We get the right thing.

00:54:25.680 --> 00:54:29.085
By the way, our GDP
numbers don't reflect that.

00:54:29.085 --> 00:54:34.850
If you were back in 1955
buying shoes that bothered you,

00:54:34.850 --> 00:54:38.030
buying medicines
that made you sick,

00:54:38.030 --> 00:54:41.150
things like that, because you
couldn't read those reviews,

00:54:41.150 --> 00:54:44.270
you had a salesman
who wasn't unbiased.

00:54:44.270 --> 00:54:46.320
That's all you could
get information from.

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:48.780
So I think our human
welfare has gone up

00:54:48.780 --> 00:54:52.360
much more than GDP has gone up.

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:55.370
So there's a real question
about the productivity numbers

00:54:55.370 --> 00:54:57.000
and the outcome numbers.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.450
So what you talk about
are wonderful things.

00:54:59.450 --> 00:55:04.150
But offsetting that there are
risks on the other side that

00:55:04.150 --> 00:55:08.540
phishing that is malicious can
be pursued more dramatically.

00:55:08.540 --> 00:55:12.580
Well, that's why we use that
word phishing and with a "ph."

00:55:12.580 --> 00:55:15.420
It goes both ways.

00:55:15.420 --> 00:55:19.790
I'm reminded that ISIS is
a product of the internet.

00:55:19.790 --> 00:55:23.560
Apparently, their ability--
the whole business model

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:28.240
of the Islamic State
is to recruit fanatics

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:30.000
from all over the world.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.320
And they have a
way to do that now.

00:55:32.320 --> 00:55:34.640
And it's creating
a real problem.

00:55:34.640 --> 00:55:36.680
So I don't know where
all this is going net,

00:55:36.680 --> 00:55:39.430
but I think it's important
that people at Google

00:55:39.430 --> 00:55:42.840
maintain a sort of
philosophic and moral stance

00:55:42.840 --> 00:55:43.810
about what they do.

00:55:43.810 --> 00:55:46.810
And they already are doing that
as I said at the beginning,

00:55:46.810 --> 00:55:49.340
and it is important
to keep that up.

00:55:49.340 --> 00:55:50.390
Yeah.

00:55:50.390 --> 00:55:52.280
AUDIENCE: So I
have two comments.

00:55:52.280 --> 00:55:55.366
One is about physicians
and licensing.

00:55:55.366 --> 00:55:56.740
I once proposed
to a friend who's

00:55:56.740 --> 00:55:59.210
a physician that that
was a means of limiting

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:02.630
the number of doctors
and keeping costs up.

00:56:02.630 --> 00:56:05.630
And she told me that, well,
actually it's the opposite.

00:56:05.630 --> 00:56:09.630
In the cities where we have
more doctors per capita,

00:56:09.630 --> 00:56:11.620
the medical expenses
are much higher.

00:56:11.620 --> 00:56:13.490
And so the more
doctors you have,

00:56:13.490 --> 00:56:16.105
the more you spend on them.

00:56:16.105 --> 00:56:16.980
ROBERT SHILLER: Yeah.

00:56:16.980 --> 00:56:18.610
AUDIENCE: And so
I have a question,

00:56:18.610 --> 00:56:19.300
what you think of that.

00:56:19.300 --> 00:56:21.130
And then I have another
question follow up,

00:56:21.130 --> 00:56:23.510
which is in the press we've
seen a lot of articles

00:56:23.510 --> 00:56:25.710
recently about
the cost of drugs,

00:56:25.710 --> 00:56:30.360
and how drug companies are
buying up old generic drugs

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:32.167
and combining them
in interesting ways,

00:56:32.167 --> 00:56:33.750
and then charging
essentially whatever

00:56:33.750 --> 00:56:36.560
they want for them, because
they are the only supplier.

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:38.090
They really have a monopoly.

00:56:38.090 --> 00:56:41.540
And I'm curious how you
think the government

00:56:41.540 --> 00:56:46.153
or the population as a whole
should deal with that issue.

00:56:48.840 --> 00:56:53.850
ROBERT SHILLER: Yeah, OK,
well, first thing there

00:56:53.850 --> 00:56:56.560
is a natural moral hazard
in the medical profession

00:56:56.560 --> 00:57:01.300
that doctors will recommend
surgery that's not necessary,

00:57:01.300 --> 00:57:02.840
because they want
to make the money.

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:06.010
And you as a client have
no ability to judge.

00:57:06.010 --> 00:57:07.494
That apparently goes on.

00:57:10.740 --> 00:57:13.350
Similar things happen in
now financial professions.

00:57:13.350 --> 00:57:16.160
Financial advisors
will steer you

00:57:16.160 --> 00:57:20.070
to client the products that
charge huge management fees

00:57:20.070 --> 00:57:21.970
for questionable activities.

00:57:21.970 --> 00:57:27.250
These are all part of
the phishing equilibrium.

00:57:27.250 --> 00:57:30.710
So what do we do about that?

00:57:30.710 --> 00:57:34.170
Well, that's a big and
long and complicated story.

00:57:34.170 --> 00:57:37.790
One thing is I think
that there is something

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:39.920
about appealing to ethics.

00:57:39.920 --> 00:57:43.870
And also you're asking doctors
to sign an oath of loyalty

00:57:43.870 --> 00:57:45.490
to their client.

00:57:45.490 --> 00:57:47.860
I was proposing
in one of my books

00:57:47.860 --> 00:57:56.240
that right now we have a tax
subsidy for financial advice,

00:57:56.240 --> 00:57:58.830
that is it's
deductible, but I think

00:57:58.830 --> 00:58:02.050
that we should make two
changes in that deductibility.

00:58:02.050 --> 00:58:06.060
One is it should be a tax
credit rather than a deduction,

00:58:06.060 --> 00:58:08.910
because the people who need
financial advice the most

00:58:08.910 --> 00:58:12.250
are low income who generally
don't have any advantage

00:58:12.250 --> 00:58:14.130
to itemizing.

00:58:14.130 --> 00:58:17.170
The other thing is that I
think financial advisors should

00:58:17.170 --> 00:58:19.890
get a government
subsidy of this form

00:58:19.890 --> 00:58:23.000
only if they sign
an oath of loyalty

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:26.470
to their client meaning that
they will not steer them

00:58:26.470 --> 00:58:32.370
toward products that are
more lucrative for them.

00:58:32.370 --> 00:58:36.940
So that would create, I think
a financial advice profession

00:58:36.940 --> 00:58:38.830
that resembles the
medical profession.

00:58:38.830 --> 00:58:44.820
I think most doctors don't
schedule you for surgery

00:58:44.820 --> 00:58:47.190
that you don't need.

00:58:47.190 --> 00:58:49.710
And that's especially
true, because they

00:58:49.710 --> 00:58:52.140
have signed some kind of oath.

00:58:52.140 --> 00:58:55.170
And they could be
sued for malpractice.

00:58:55.170 --> 00:58:58.680
So it's partly a fear, but
I think it goes beyond that.

00:58:58.680 --> 00:59:00.820
People do have some morals.

00:59:00.820 --> 00:59:02.610
And if you said you
would do something,

00:59:02.610 --> 00:59:08.430
you probably would just,
most people will just do it.

00:59:08.430 --> 00:59:13.070
So buying up drugs and
raising the price, that

00:59:13.070 --> 00:59:15.200
is something that we,
it was in the news

00:59:15.200 --> 00:59:18.340
recently for an
outrageous example.

00:59:18.340 --> 00:59:21.350
I can think of free market
justifications for that

00:59:21.350 --> 00:59:23.790
if that additional profits
would then eventually

00:59:23.790 --> 00:59:28.560
go to more drug research
that would help.

00:59:28.560 --> 00:59:31.090
Maybe it's expensive
to do the research,

00:59:31.090 --> 00:59:33.010
and so maybe some
drugs have to be high.

00:59:33.010 --> 00:59:34.426
AUDIENCE: The
government funds it.

00:59:34.426 --> 00:59:36.590
ROBERT SHILLER:
Well, anyway, you've

00:59:36.590 --> 00:59:39.610
brought an example of
a questionable activity

00:59:39.610 --> 00:59:42.950
that I don't have
answers to all of them.

00:59:42.950 --> 00:59:45.760
This book is just a
general thought piece

00:59:45.760 --> 00:59:50.250
that's supposed to change
people's deep assumptions

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:52.160
about the free market.

00:59:52.160 --> 00:59:53.160
I think I'm out of time.

00:59:53.160 --> 00:59:55.410
Is that right?

00:59:55.410 --> 00:59:56.580
OK, well, thank you.

00:59:56.580 --> 01:00:00.230
[APPLAUSE]

